P2P Loans: Prosper Dataset¶

by Vasileios Garyfallos¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

For this project I have selected a dataset from Prosper Loan, a California-based FinTech which facilitates peer-to-peer loans. Prospective borrowers request personal loans through Prosper, with individual or institutional investors choosing who to fund. The loans, worth anywhere from \$2,000 to \\$40,000, are distributed through Prosper. Prosper also collects and allocates payments and interests from borrowers to lenders. Investors make lending decisions based on a borrower's credit score, rating, and history, as well as the category of the loan (source). As someone also working in the FinTech industry, in mobile banking, I am excited to learn more about a different aspect of the sector.

The dataset itself was provided through Udacity's Data Analyst Nanodegree program, but similar historical data can also be obtained directly through Prosper via an API, as long as the requester has a valid Prosper account (source). Documentation for the dataset is available through Udacity or Prosper.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Wow, this dataset is pretty large! It contains 113,937 rows and 81 columns. Luckily, no rows have been duplicated and it seems like all columns have been assigned the correct datatype. However, many columns are missing data - anywhere from 25 ('BorrowerAPR') to over 100,000 ('GroupKey'). Normally, I would also now view some statistical information using .describe(), but given the large size of the dataset I want to first think deeper about how to strategically investigate some key features.

What is the main feature of interest in your dataset?¶

There's a lot of information available in this dataset - almost too much! After re-reading through the documentation, I've decided to focus on the borrower rate. I want to explore borrowers' economic demographics in relation to this rate. My assumption is that borrowers in better economic standing receive more favorable interest rates as they are considered by investors to be less risky. But is my assumption true?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

To answer these questions, I will need to create a smaller dataset containing relevant information about the borrower's financial health (e.g. 'Occupation', 'EmploymentStatus', 'EmploymentStatusDuration', 'IsBorrowerHomeowner', 'CreditScoreRangeLower', 'CreditScoreRangeUpper', 'CurrentCreditLines', 'OpenCreditLines', 'DebtToIncomeRatio', 'IncomeRange', 'IncomeVerifiable', and 'StatedMonthlyIncome').

The statistical summary already tells me a lot about my dataset and my main feature of interest, the borrower rate. I see that the rate ranges from 0 to about .50, with most borrowers receiving a rate between 0.13 and 0.25.

The credit score columns may contain some incorrect information, as a credit score only ranges from 300 to 850 (source). However, these columns reveal scores between 0 and 899.

Borrowers tend to have between 7 and 13 lines of credit, with most of them open lines. There are some potential outliers in these columns, as the maximum number of current credit lines in 59 and the standard deviation is only about 5.27.

The debt-to-income ratio, as explained in Prosper's documentation, can be more than 100% - it just means that the borrower had more debt than income. While this max value still appears to be an outlier, considering that the 75th percentile is 0.31, it is not necessarily inaccurate.

The stated monthly income column reveals a large spread, with most borrowers earning between 3,200 and 6,828 USD per month and one lucky borrower earning over 1,750,00 USD (although this value seems suspicious).

Credit¶

The lower and upper bounds of credit scores range from approximately 450 to nearly 900, with the majority of borrowers having a credit score between 600 and 700. The spread between the lower and upper bounds appears to be around 50 points. The distribution is bimodal and slightly left-skewed, with the dataset representing more borrowers that have better credit. This may imply that those with better credit receive more loans, as would be expected. However, without having information on the credit scores of borrowers who did not receive a loan, it's impossible to test this hypothesis.

Moving forward with my analysis, I will use the lower bound of the credit score to serve as a proxy for the actual score. This is a more conservative approach than selecting the upper bound.

Univariate Exploration Summary¶

The borrower rate, my main feature of interest, proved to have the most surprising distribution - almost bimodal in nature, with high spikes for rates around 0.25, 0.32 and 0.35 percent.

Nearly all borrowers are employed in some form, with a heavily right-skewed employment duration distribution. I chose to remove all rows where the employment status was unavailable, as well as combined all the types of employment into one category. I also transformed the duration variable from monthly to yearly duration. I used a log transformation on the employment duration distribution, but the data does not appear to be log-normal. Given my interest in borrowers' economic conditions, I think there are other variables - such as income range - that are better suited to my analysis, so I will not continue to explore further transformations on the employment duration variable.

The debt-to-income ratio is also heavily right-skewed, with most borrowers having debt-to-income ratios less than 0.30. Due to the large amount of outliers, I chose to remove any ratio over 1.5.

Out of all borrowers receiving some form of income, the majority earn between 25,000 and under 75,000 USD. Surprisingly, the third most-common borrower earned over 100,000 USD. In order to better view the data, I removed missing data (marked as "Not displayed" in the dataset) and combined the "Not employed" and "\$0" values as well as limited the x-axis to account for the outlier I saw in the statistical summary.

The credit score distribution was slightly left-skewed, with the dataset representing more borrowers with better credit.

Bivariate Exploration Summary¶

I observed the clearest relationship between the borrower rate and credit score, where borrowers with higher credit scores tend to enjoy lower interest rates than borrowers with lower scores. Surprisingly, a similar relationship did not exist between the borrower rate and number of lines of credit. However, a weak positive relationship was observed between lines of credit and the debt-to-income ratio. Borrowers in higher income ranges received on average lower rates, as did borrowers who owned homes.

Multivariate Exploration Summary¶

The negative relationship between borrower rate and credit score can be enhanced by other financial features, such as the borrower's homeowner status, number of credit lines, and income. However, lower earners (under 50,000 USD) experience a weaker relationship than higher earners.
